## Architecture
- Keep UI, application logic, and data-access concerns separated.
- Route and page components should stay thin; delegate to feature modules and hooks.
- Business rules belong in domain-oriented modules, hooks, or services—not scattered in leaf components.
- Network and persistence boundaries belong behind clear modules (API client, query layer, storage helpers).

## Module boundaries
- Prefer feature-oriented folders when the codebase grows; avoid a single undifferentiated `components` dump.
- Keep shared UI primitives small and reusable; avoid coupling them to feature-specific types.
- Avoid circular imports between features; lift shared types or utilities to a neutral layer when needed.

## Construction and wiring
- Prefer explicit dependency injection through hooks and module factories over hidden singletons.
- Do not use global mutable state for core application dependencies except where the platform requires it (e.g. router context) and the scope is explicit.
- Keep app bootstrap and providers in dedicated entry/layout modules.

## Configuration
- Treat public configuration as explicit build-time or runtime input (env vars, injected config).
- Validate configuration at startup where practical; fail fast on invalid required configuration for the current environment.
- Never hardcode secrets, tokens, or environment-specific endpoints in source control.
